<BlogPost
  title="Nothing to Hack"
  description="No servers, no databases, no user accounts. The best security is having almost nothing to protect."
  date="2026-04-13"
>

  <p>
    Most productivity apps store your data on their servers. Your notes, tasks, and calendar events sit in a company's database, behind login screens and payment systems. If that company gets breached — and breaches happen regularly — your data is part of it.
  </p>

  <p>
    Pikos doesn't have any of that.
  </p>

  <h2>No servers</h2>

  <p>
    There is no server. The app runs entirely on your computer and stores everything in a file on your hard drive. It doesn't connect to the internet during normal use. There's nothing to breach because there's nothing running on my end.
  </p>

  <h2>No accounts</h2>

  <p>
    You open the app and start using it. There's no sign-up, no email, no password. I don't know who you are, what you've written, or how many pages you've created. There's no list of users to leak because there are no users — just people running the app on their own machines.
  </p>

  <h2>No payment details</h2>

  <p>
    The desktop app is a free download from this site. No payment involved, no credit card, no billing address. When the Mac App Store and iPhone versions ship, Apple will handle those purchases. I'll never see your card number or Apple ID.
  </p>

  <h2>No email, no mailing list</h2>

  <p>
    There's no newsletter sign-up, no "enter your email for updates," no mailing list. I will never email you because I don't have your email address. If you want to follow along, there's the <a href="/blog" class="text-orange-500 hover:underline">blog</a> and the <a href="/release-notes" class="text-orange-500 hover:underline">release notes</a>. Both public, no sign-up.
  </p>

  <h2>Less infrastructure, fewer things to go wrong</h2>

  <p>
    Every system a company runs is something that can be compromised — their database, their login system, their payment processor, their email service. The fewer systems, the fewer things that can go wrong.
  </p>

  <p>
    Pikos has almost no infrastructure. This website is a simple static site. The app is a program that runs on your computer. That's it. The security isn't built from layers of firewalls and monitoring — it comes from the fact that there's almost nothing there to attack.
  </p>

  <h2>Your device matters</h2>

  <p>
    The flip side: since everything is stored on your computer, your data is only as safe as your device. If someone gets into your unlocked laptop, they can see your Pikos data — the same way they could read your documents or browse your photos.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is true of every app on your computer, but it's worth saying out loud because Pikos keeps all your notes and tasks locally. A few things that help:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Use a strong password on your computer and lock it when you step away</li>
    <li>Turn on disk encryption — on Mac, it's called FileVault (in System Settings → Privacy & Security)</li>
    <li>Keep your operating system updated</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    With most apps, a security breach happens at the company and affects everyone at once. With Pikos, the risk is limited to your own device. For most people, a locked laptop with disk encryption is more than enough.
  </p>

</BlogPost>
